For a Crypto Game: Treeverse Review

Chris Davis

3 days ago ⋅  16 min read

Key Takeaways

  • Treeverse is a classless, cross-platform fantasy MMORPG built on Immutable zkEVM, where players journey through the open world of Lorwick, fighting monsters, clearing dungeons, and crafting gear.
  • While the gameplay offers stunning visuals and many enjoyable elements, the overall systems feel too shallow and repetitive, lacking the complexity and depth that typically sustain long-term player engagement in the MMORPG genre.
  • The most pressing issue for Treeverse is its lack of genre-defining social features. Without guilds, PVP, or a player-driven economy, the game struggles to create the social dynamics that can drive strong network effects.
  • Despite receiving a low rating, Treeverse has significant potential. As a mobile-first MMORPG, it targets a high-growth market in a genre that has demonstrated strong product-market fit with crypto-native players.
  • If Treeverse can deepen gameplay systems and add missing core MMORPG elements, it stands a strong chance of closing the gap between its current state and its potential and evolving into a genuinely compelling MMORPG experience.

Introduction

“The game is really fun… for a crypto game.”

For a crypto game. It’s the caveat that has historically defined the crypto gaming sector. A reminder that although the game is fun, it’s not that fun, so don’t get your hopes up. One part a defense of one’s own taste, one part a defense of the industry more broadly.

However, it’s time to accept that we’re no longer in 2021. If we truly believe that incorporating crypto elements into gaming is a net positive for players, it’s important to drop the caveat and start evaluating these games against industry leaders. Our hope with this game review series is to offer opinions without training wheels, examining crypto games with the same scrutiny we would apply to any Web2 title.

Given Treeverse’s recent Season 1 release, reviewing this game seemed like as good a starting point as any. Plus, my longstanding affection for MMORPGs sets a high bar, and I was genuinely excited to see how this game measures up to the genre-defining titles I grew up with.

In this review, I’ll first provide general context on the game, then share my high-level opinions, break down individual gameplay categories, and finally deliver a cumulative rating and closing thoughts.

Game Overview and Context

Treeverse, developed by Web3 studio Endless Clouds, is a classless, cross-platform fantasy MMORPG built on Immutable zkEVM. Players begin in the city of Lorwick and embark on an open-world journey to locate the World Tree, fighting monsters, clearing dungeons, and crafting gear along the way. The game’s central loop revolves around dungeon runs, loot upgrades, and leveling up, with resource gathering and questing present but currently rudimentary.

Treeverse’s development dates back to 2021. The team launched its Genesis Land NFTs in August 2021 and by October had raised a seed round at a $25 million valuation led by Animoca Brands. Since then, the game has undergone an aggressive transformation, evolving from a socially driven 2D pixelated browser game into the mobile-first MMORPG it is today. Its three NFT collections (NFTrees, Treeverse Plots, and Timeless Characters) currently have no functional in-game utility, though the team has indicated plans for future integration.

The recent Season 1 release introduces a 21-day incentive campaign distributing 2.6% of the native $END token to top players. Rewards are split across daily quest completions, skill maxing, and leaderboard performance, with eligibility requiring ownership of either a collectible NFT or a $5 “boost” NFT.

High-Level Thoughts

Note: This review is based on ~20 hours of personal gameplay plus research into later-stage gameplay.

I genuinely wanted to love this game. On paper, it hits all the marks of something I’d sink too many hours into: fantasy MMORPG, open world, classless, gentle aesthetics, mobile-first design. But in its current form, Treeverse feels more like a rough draft than a polished release. While it features the key building blocks of an MMORPG, such as skilling, crafting, combat, quests, and social play, most of these elements lack depth. More importantly, the absence of core MMO pillars like PVP, a player-to-player economy, or integrated guild systems makes the experience feel hollow compared to its genre peers.

That said, Treeverse has significant potential. The mobile-first approach targets a high-growth market underserved in crypto gaming, and the MMORPG format displays product-market fit with crypto native players (as Cambria’s success shows). Adding a robust in-game economy and risk-based systems could make Treeverse a strong fit for this audience. Still, I hesitate to recommend investing resources in those features while core MMORPG elements are missing.

With incentives temporarily boosting engagement, the team has a narrow window to deepen gameplay before a likely drop in retention. If their ambition is to attract Web2 mobile players, the pressure is even greater, as that audience won’t overlook basic missing systems or paper over flaws with token rewards.

Given that the game has been in development for four years, I have some doubts about whether this leap is realistic. Still, if Treeverse can close the gap between its potential and its execution, it’s the kind of game I could see myself sinking an irresponsible number of hours into, regardless of any play-to-earn upside.

With all that said, let’s dive into individual review categories. In the following sections, we’ll cover ratings and commentary on:

  • Visuals & Audio
  • Gameplay Mechanics
  • Progression & Customization
  • Questing & Content Design
  • Social & Player Interaction
  • Technical Performance

Visuals & Audio (7/10)

Visuals

From the moment of opening the app, Treeverse delivers a warm, peaceful visual aesthetic reminiscent of The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild. The muted, earthy tones of floating ships and colossal land masses against an expansive blue sky create a fantasy dreamscape that heightens the anticipation of entering the game’s universe.

The design maintains strong continuity between the 2D login screen and the 3D in-game environments, which range from lush forests with towering trees to massive architectural structures suspended in the clouds. Enemy designs vary across regions, with “slimes” as the main recurring creature, while gear evolves visually from basic iron equipment to more ornate enchanted weapons. Combat effects feel crisp, and physics are generally sound, highlighting the design team’s clear effort in crafting an immersive atmosphere that captures attention and retains it over extended periods.

Audio

The game’s music is pleasant, but nothing to write home about. It’s about what you’d imagine the output of an AI prompt like “compose an orchestral-driven fantasy MMORPG soundtrack” would sound like, which, nowadays, probably produces a fairly decent quality soundtrack.

Audio engineering, however, could use a good deal of improvement. The balance between music and sound effects skews too heavily toward sound effects for my taste, at times completely overshadowing the music. Additionally, the sound effects lack nuanced spatial dynamics, making it hard to distinguish how far or close enemies are, which was particularly noticeable in dungeons. Despite normally enjoying sound effects, I opted to turn them off, as they often broke the immersion into the game’s universe.

Gameplay Mechanics & Systems (6/10)

Combat

Combat in Treeverse is far from an idle experience, especially during boss battles. Although the move selection is sparse, with a maximum of three special abilities per weapon, a standard attack, and a roll move, it doesn’t feel limiting in the heat of battle. An important strategic element is switching between ranged and melee weapons. While there’s always the option to go full Leeroy Jenkins and rush in swinging, at certain times it’s more effective to pick off select targets from a distance and pause to heal between fights. Despite there being swords, claws, bows, and staffs to choose from, most players alternate between swords and staffs, using swords to deal the majority of damage and staffs for ranged attacks and healing. In its current form, this strategy feels slightly overpowered but not so much that it makes boss battles unenjoyable.

All moves outside of the basic attack require energy, which depletes with each use and is restored by landing attacks. This contrasts with many RPGs where special moves are gated by time-based cooldowns. I personally liked this constraint, as it forces you to remain active in combat and take risks to land basic hits before tossing in a higher-damage move or a heal. Similar to energy, HP doesn’t auto-regenerate, requiring either a healing spell or a consumable, such as a health potion, to recover.

One technical issue with combat that needs to be addressed is input latency. Although the latency isn’t severe, it has a noticeable impact on combat since timing plays such a central role in battle. In Treeverse, a short lag can mean the difference between dodging a high-damage attack and ending up back in the respawn area.

Resources & Crafting

The lack of diversity in resource gathering and crafting is the biggest contributor to the mediocre rating in this category. There are three skills to level up: lumbering (chopping down trees), mining, and fishing. For each skill, there are only one to two types of resources to gather, a far cry from the variety offered in landmark MMORPGs such as Runescape. Furthermore, you can harvest all resources right from the start, eliminating the dopamine hit that comes from unlocking new resources as you level up. In my opinion, there should be at least three to four resources per skill, unlocking in tandem with skill progression. On a positive note, however, the respawn timer for resources lands right in the Goldilocks zone: not too long, not too short.

Crafting offers more variety than gathering, but still falls flat compared to other MMORPGs. Unlocking crafting blueprints depends on clearing dungeons, with no individual crafting skills to level up. While some might find that this design choice saves time, it significantly limits how much customization you can put into your gameplay.

My main gripe with crafting, though, is less about skills and more about economics. The balance between gold earned in dungeons and the price of materials at the general store feels unbalanced. Ideally, crafting would be necessarily downstream from resource gathering. However, due to the low material prices, I found it much more efficient to purchase the resources needed to craft gear. This rendered resource gathering largely unnecessary, minimizing what I believe should be a core component of gameplay.

Dungeons

Dungeons follow the classic structure of continuous grinding through heterogeneous groups of enemies with varying difficulty levels and abilities, culminating in an epic boss battle.

Boss battles are one of Treeverse’s strongest features. While it’s generally possible to mash your way through lower-level enemies, fighting bosses requires carefully timed hits, rolls, movements, and heals. Each boss employs a unique set of moves that necessitate adopting new strategies from dungeon to dungeon, and choices at a granular level have a notable impact. For example, you may need to swap out armor to run fast enough to avoid a specific attack.

Despite my overall positive sentiment toward dungeon design, the drops from bosses could benefit from more variety. Currently, bosses only drop their respective “core,” an item needed for crafting gear. While this reinforces the loop of clearing dungeons to upgrade equipment, the one-dimensional design feels uninspired. Diversifying drops to include rare weapons or randomized item combinations would add an element of chance, injecting excitement into dungeon clears.

Additionally, there seems to be an overabundance of health potions scattered along the way to the final boss. While generally a helpful feature, the sheer quantity could be dialed back to make boss battles more challenging.

Progression & Customization (3/10)

Leveling

Overall, it felt like the power curve needs adjustment once you hit level ~10. As I progressed, dungeons started to feel a bit too easy, which made leveling up feel more like a chore than an adventure. Additionally, the amount of experience gained from dungeons relative to the experience needed to level up seems to decline substantially as you advance.

These issues wouldn’t be as significant if the game loop didn’t depend so heavily on dungeons. However, given that dungeon runs are at the core of progression, they end up highlighting the game’s shortcomings; most notably, the minimal number of quests.

I believe these factors have contributed to an increasing player preference for grinding XP by running laps around a small track in an area called Flogen Isles, repeatedly killing the same handful of monsters. Yes, it’s mind-numbing. But at the moment, it’s the most efficient method for leveling up.

Character Customization

For a classless MMORPG, Treeverse offers disappointingly few options for customizing your character. I believe the issue stems primarily from bundling much of the skill progression under general level-based progression.

In this system, everyone’s progression is essentially uniform. When you clear a dungeon in a new area, you unlock blueprints for crafting new weapons and gear, as well as materials like steel bars and iron fittings. This stands in contrast to other classless MMORPGs, such as Runescape, where your ability to craft and utilize gear and materials depends on leveling individual skills like fletching, smithing, attack, ranged, magic, defense, and crafting.

By bucketing these individual skills under a single leveling system, the game removes opportunities for players to tailor progression toward specific end goals. In a purely skill-based system, for example, a player aiming to create a high-DPS character might focus on leveling up attack and smithing to craft and equip powerful melee weapons, while deprioritizing skills that unlock stronger armor or ranged gear.

This design trades customization for simpler, more streamlined gameplay, which is understandable, given that combat emphasizes improvement within a set of constraints. However, I would prefer to see some of the non-combat-related activities, such as smithing or fletching, follow their own independent progression paths.

Questing & Narrative Design (1/10)

Quests and narrative are design areas where Treeverse falls completely flat. The game offers only seven quests, all located in the starting town. Aside from the initial tutorial quest, they mostly play out as fetch-based side quests, lacking a cohesive storyline tying them together. For players who prefer grinding skill progression and dungeons, this may not be a dealbreaker. However, I believe quests provide essential structure for most players and deliver lore that emotionally connects players to a game.

The absence of meaningful quests and narrative significantly reduces my willingness to invest substantial time in Treeverse, overshadowing many of the game’s enjoyable aspects. While there are other more urgent areas for improvement, such as expanding social features and diversifying resource systems, I believe narrative development should rank high on the team’s priority list if they hope to scale and retain their player base over an extended period of time.

Social & Player Interaction (3/10)

Player-to-player interactions are a defining characteristic of MMORPGs. In a modern MMO, you’d typically expect an embedded guild system, friends lists, player-versus-player (PVP) combat, and a dynamic player-driven economy. These features not only help form the core network effects that scale player bases and lower acquisition costs, but they also play a significant role in retention. These downstream effects are especially important in crypto gaming, where player behavior tends to be mercenary, hopping from one incentive campaign to the next.

For a game that positions itself around social gameplay, it’s striking how many core multiplayer elements are missing. The absence of a player-driven economy and PVP severely restricts the variety of playstyles available, narrowing the ways players can engage and find enjoyment. This omission feels especially stark when compared to other successful crypto MMORPGs, such as Cambria, which deliberately embrace economic complexity and risk-based systems.

If more core social elements were integrated, this rating would likely jump by several points. Even in its current state, the game becomes noticeably more enjoyable and efficient when played with others. As long as you land one hit on an enemy, you gain the full XP from the kill, making group play far more effective for leveling. To fully capitalize on this, it would be helpful to have a friends list or an in-game guild system that players can engage with. As it stands now, players are left exchanging Discord handles via chat, which breaks immersion and will ultimately reduce engagement over time.

Technical Performance (3/10)

To say that the raw technical performance of the game was frustrating would be an understatement. For the first 72 hours of the season, half of my time spent “gaming” involved either attempting to log in on different servers in the hope that one would load, restarting the app when it froze, or uttering obscenities after losing all progress in a dungeon due to a crash.

Normally, this experience would warrant a 1/10 rating for technical performance. However, after the team pushed a server update on April 29th, performance has improved to a passable level. There are still occasional issues with loading, freezing, and crashes, but I anticipate that the team will continue to improve stability over the course of the season.

Final Verdict

Taking the average across all category ratings places Treeverse at roughly a 4/10. This cumulative score generally aligns with the impression I had in mind before breaking down each category independently. The overall lack of content diversity, combined with the absence of core MMORPG features, makes rating it any higher feel like charity.

Beyond the suggestions provided throughout this review, I would prefer to see Treeverse lean further into cryptonative elements. The current state of crypto gaming suggests that product-market fit is easier to achieve when building at the extremes. Games that lean fully crypto native, like Cambria, and those that embrace mass-market strategies, like NFL Rivals, have both found success, but for opposite reasons. Playing in the middle often results in failing to capture either crypto natives, who tend to prefer high-risk, high-reward dynamics, or traditional gamers, who often carry a built-in skepticism toward crypto integrations.

As a mobile-first MMORPG, Treeverse is well-positioned to reach a wider audience than browser-based crypto games, which often suffer from degraded performance on mobile, even when using PWAs. Moreover, it benefits from a second-mover advantage, with the opportunity to learn from the missteps of the first generation of risk-based, economy-driven games. While this direction carries trade-offs, I believe it ultimately offers the best chance at long-term success.

Despite the less-than-favorable rating, Treeverse is, frankly, one of the more enjoyable crypto games I’ve played. If I were to apply the familiar “for a crypto game” caveat, I’d give it closer to a 7/10. More importantly, I strongly believe the game has the potential to reach this level even when benchmarked against Web2 games. While it’s unlikely I’ll be sinking too much time into it right now, Treeverse is a project I’ll be keeping a close eye on going forward.
